   "source": [
    "(a) Even though the Bayes Decision Boundary is Linear, we expect QDA to perform better on the training set because of overfit. But on the test set we expect LDA to perform better because of increase variance in the case of QDA."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "0b97583d-af5f-456c-bfc9-2d033dd35d88",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "(b) In case on non-linear Bayes Decision boundary we expect QDA to perform better on both QDA and LDA, because QDA being more complex method will generally capture more of pattern in the dataset, provided the sample size is not too small."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "fa958f1b-8870-4ba3-bfac-8659e3d0b524",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "(c) In general we will expect QDA test prediction accuracy to improve relative to LDA. Because as we know QDA requires way more data points compared to LDA to the calculated coefficient will have more accuracy with increase no. of data points."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "99edcb54-3cf1-47e2-9778-1c081cd42339",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "(d) No, because QDA requires comparatively more no. of data points so QDA won't perform better always, it can only perform better if we have large no. of data points."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "0cbfb0c9-f4f6-4875-b37e-5a7bdcfee160",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "(d)* Modified, based on feedback from ChatGPT: Although QDA is flexible enough to model a linear decision boundary, this additional flexibility leads to higher variance. When the true boundary is linear, LDA’s stronger assumptions reduce variance and typically yield better test performance."
   ]
  }
